    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-10-22T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-10-22T21:00:00-05:00" n="855"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d855">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.48/2189: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-10-23T11:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 23, 1941—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1675. Embassy’s 1414, September 7, 9 a.m.,<note n="38" xml:id="d855fn1">See
                        footnote 19, <ref target="#pg_791">p. 791</ref>.</note> Japanese seizure of
                    Red Cross cracked wheat Canton. A reply dated October 21 to the Embassy’s
                    representations has been received from the Foreign Office stating that the wheat
                    was seized by the Japanese Navy while being smuggled from Hong Kong in violation
                    of the Japanese blockade, a fact which is recognized by persons connected with
                    the Canton Relief Society, presumably a Japanese sponsored organization.</p>
                <p>There is no denial that the wheat was sold commercially.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department via Shanghai, Chungking, Peiping, Hong Kong, Canton.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
